Here is a detailed solution for writing a JavaScript function that checks if an array of 5 numbers contains any prime numbers and prints them:

```js
function checkPrimes(arr) {

  // Loop through each number in the array
  for(let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {

    // Assume number is prime 
    let isPrime = true;

    // Cannot be prime if less than 2
    if(arr[i] < 2) {
      isPrime = false;
    }
    else {
      // Check if divisible by any number up to the square root
      for(let j = 2; j <= Math.sqrt(arr[i]); j++) {
        if(arr[i] % j == 0) {
          isPrime = false;
          break; 
        }
      }
    }

    // If prime, print the number
    if(isPrime) {
      console.log(arr[i] + " is prime"); 
    }

  }

}

// Usage
let numbers = [2, 5, 8, 11, 15]; 
checkPrimes(numbers);

// Prints: 
// 2 is prime
// 5 is prime 
// 11 is prime
```

The key steps are:

1. Loop through each number in the input array 
2. Check if the number is less than 2 (can't be prime)
3. Otherwise, check if it's divisible by any number up to its square root
4. If no divisors found, it is prime - so print it
5. Call the function by passing an array with 5 numbers

